==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|absinthium}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἀψίνθιον}}, {{m|grc|ἀσπίνθιον}}. The Ancient Greek word is of uncertain origin, albeit recognized as foreign (E.R. Wharton): underlain by a pre-Greek [[w:Pelasgians#Pelasgian_as_pre-Indo-European|Pelasgian]] word, marked by the non-Indoeuropean consonant complex νθ.
May be from {{etyl|fa|en}} {{m|fa|sc=fa-Arab|اسپند|tr=ispand||wild rue}}. See also [[w:Absinthe#Etymology|Absinthe on Wikipedia]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈsɪn.θi.m̩/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{label|en|now|rare}} The common [[wormwood]] (''[[Artemisia absinthium]]''), an [[intensely]] bitter herb used in the production of [[absinthe]] and [[vermouth]], and as a [[tonic]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED>{{cite-book|editor=Brown, Lesley|title=The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary|year=1933|edition=5th|year_published=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, UK|isbn=978-0-19-860575-7|page=9}}</ref>
# The dried leaves and flowering tops of the [[wormwood]] plant; [[absinthe oil]].<ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=5}}</ref>
